Echoes of a Fallen King
A Skyrim Campaign Adventure for an Adept Tier Party
Estimated Play Time: 6-8 hours (2 sessions recommended)
Party Size: 5 players
Difficulty: Scaled for Adept Tier (Party has 4 AP)
Reward: 1200 Gold per player, one powerful and two moderate enchanted items, and 1 Advancement Point

Adventure Summary
Fresh from their morally complex resolution in Falkreath, the party finds themselves in Solitude, summoned by High King Torygg. The hours before their sundown audience become a crucible of personal revelations: vampires must hunt in a watchful city, divine blessings manifest with terrible costs, and long-buried legacies resurface. At the Blue Palace, they will meet an accomplished solo adventurer named Krusp Fanck and be tested by the highest authorities in Skyrim. Those who prove worthy will be chartered as the founding members of the Skyrim Wardens—just in time to witness their patron's assassination and the shattering of their newfound purpose.

SESSION 1: THE WARDEN'S AUDITION
Part I: The Calm Before the Storm
Setting: The Winking Skeever, Morning After Arrival
The party awakens in the Winking Skeever after their first night in Solitude. The contrast to Falkreath is absolute—warm sunlight, the smell of fresh bread, distant music from the Bards College, and the rhythmic march of Imperial soldiers.
Read Aloud:
"The morning sun of Solitude streams through the windows of the Winking Skeever, a stark contrast to the oppressive gloom of Falkreath. The city outside is alive with the sounds of commerce, marching Legionnaires, and the distant, beautiful music of the Bards College. You have had a night of safe, if not entirely restful, sleep.
As you gather in the common room, the inn's door swings open. The cheerful noise of the tavern quiets as Legate Quintus steps inside, his polished armor gleaming. He scans the room, his eyes finding your table, and approaches with a purposeful stride."
Scene 1: The Royal Schedule
Quintus's Delivery:
(Quintus stops at your table, his presence commanding the attention of the room. He gives a formal, crisp nod to the party as a whole, his gaze lingering for a moment on Davinia with a sign of recognition.)
"Good morning. I trust you slept well. I am Legate Quintus. I am here to follow up on the High King's summons you received."
"Your reputation has reached the throne, and the King requests a private audience with your company to discuss a matter of grave importance to the realm. You are to present yourselves at the main gate of the Blue Palace precisely at sundown today."
"Until then, the day is yours. His Majesty was clear that you should have time to rest, resupply, and see the capital. But do not be late. The King is making a specific exception in his schedule for you."
GM Note: This dialogue acknowledges the prior summons, sets the ticking clock, and explicitly creates the window for the Order of business. By having Quintus enter and address the group, it ensures all players are present and understand the stakes.

Part II: The Capital at Peace (The Sandbox)
GM Note: This section provides the tools to run the downtime in Solitude. After delivering the Royal Schedule, the GM should say:
"This gives you several hours to explore the capital, resupply, and tend to your personal affairs. What would you like to do?"
The party is now free to explore. You will then transition into the private Order of Business spotlights as the players move through the city, using the locations below as the backdrop for their scenes.
City Profile: Solitude, The Jewel of the North
Atmosphere & Core Conflict:
Solitude is a city at its peak—majestic, orderly, and prosperous. The air is crisp with the scent of sea salt and clean stone. The Core Conflict is "Imperial Order vs. Nordic Heart." The city's public face is one of law and discipline, but beneath it, the Nords grumble about the Thalmor and the ban on Talos worship. The city is a powder keg of cultural tension, held in check only by the deep respect most hold for their young High King.

GM's Sandbox Toolkit: Solitude
This document provides the location-based data for the Solitude sandbox.

Players each get a budget of 4 actions, 4 things they can do during free time in the city. The first for each player will be the order of business for their personal stories, after which they get one more thing they can go do before we move to the next player who gets the same opportunity. 

THE MARKET DISTRICT
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The Market District is the vibrant heart of Solitude. The air is filled with the smells of fresh-baked bread, aromatic spices, and the clean scent of leather. Citizens and travelers mingle in the open-air plaza, their conversations punctuated by the cheerful strumming of a student from the nearby Bards College. Stalls are laden with goods from across the Empire, and the city guard patrols with a calm, professional air. This is the picture of Imperial prosperity."
Key NPCs Present:
Sayma: Pragmatic proprietor of "Bits and Pieces" (General Goods).
Angeline Morrard: Elderly Breton alchemist at "Angeline's Aromatics."
Fihada: Bosmer master bowyer at "Fletcher."
Lisette: A talented and ambitious bard, often found near the Winking Skeever.
Evette San: A nervous spiced wine merchant with her own stall.


Player Opportunities:
Go Shopping: Players can visit the various merchants to buy, sell, and upgrade gear.
Bits and Pieces (General Goods): Sayma's preference is Gossip & Stories. She values news from the road more than a few extra septims.
Angeline's Aromatics (Alchemist): Angeline's preference is Helpful Advice. She is deeply worried about her daughter serving in the Legion and will be grateful for any reassurance or practical advice.
Fletcher (Bowyer): Fihada's preference is Professional Courtesy. He respects fellow artisans and skilled archers and will offer a better price to those who can demonstrate knowledge of his craft.


Gather Rumors: Players can speak with Lisette, who is seeking a new story for a ballad, or Evette San, who is convinced a rival sabotaged her latest shipment.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Poor. The area is crowded, well-lit, and frequently patrolled. Attempting a hunt here would be extremely risky and likely to draw the immediate attention of the City Guard.

THE TEMPLE DISTRICT
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"A sense of peace settles over you as you approach the Temple of the Divines. The grand structure offers a sanctuary from the bustle of the city. Worshippers move with quiet reverence, and the scent of incense hangs in the air. In the temple's garden, a single, struggling Gildergreen sapling stands as a symbol of hope and renewal."
Key NPCs Present:
Freir: The head priestess of the Temple.
Various other priests and acolytes tending to their duties.


Player Opportunities:
Seek Blessings: A character can receive a blessing from one of the eight shrines.
Conduct Research: The priests can be questioned about religious history, the undead, or Daedric lore, though their knowledge is filtered through dogma. Access to their library would require significant persuasion.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: None. This is consecrated ground. Vampires will feel a growing, oppressive discomfort the longer they remain, making it an unsuitable place to linger or hunt.

THE MILITARY DISTRICT (CASTLE DOUR)
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The western side of the city is dominated by Castle Dour, a grim and functional fortress that serves as the headquarters of the Imperial Legion. The air here is different—sharper, colder. The sounds are of marching feet on stone, the clang of steel on steel from the training yard, and the barked orders of officers. This is the engine of Imperial military might."
Key NPCs Present:
General Tullius & Legate Rikke: Can be seen observing drills or in strategic meetings.
Imperial Soldiers & Officers: The area is swarming with disciplined military personnel.


Player Opportunities:
Report a Crime: Players could attempt to report the dead tax collectors. The process will be bureaucratic, formal, and likely met with skepticism unless they have irrefutable proof.
Observe Drills: Players can watch the Legion train, gaining insight into their tactics, discipline, and formidable strength.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Suicidal. This is the most heavily guarded and least private area of the city. Any hostile action would be met with an overwhelming military response.

THE SOLITUDE DOCKS
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The scent of salt and fish, the cries of gulls, and the shouts of sailors hauling cargo fill the air at the Solitude Docks. Massive ships are moored at the piers, their banners representing trade companies from across Tamriel. It is a place of chaotic, thriving energy, where fortunes are made and goods from around the world flow into Skyrim."
Key NPCs Present:
Sailors & Dockworkers: A rough, transient population. Good for hearing rumors from other ports.
Addvar: A local fisherman, often found mending his nets or selling his catch.


Player Opportunities:
Gather Rumors: Sailors are a font of information about coastal raids, strange weather, and news from other provinces.
The Hunt: This is a viable, though risky, feeding ground. The dark alleys between warehouses, the rowdy tavern ("The Lonely Troll"), and the constant flow of transient people provide opportunities to find an isolated target. A failure here would quickly bring the City Guard.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: High Risk.

THE HALL OF THE DEAD
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"Set into the rock face of the city is the Hall of the Dead, Solitude's catacombs. It is a quiet, somber place, the air cool and still. Priests of Arkay tend to the remains of the recently departed, their movements slow and respectful. The silence is profound, a stark contrast to the lively city above."
Key NPCs Present:
Priests of Arkay: Somber caretakers of the dead.


Player Opportunities:
Speak with the Priests: Inquire about burial rites, local diseases, or any recent, unusual deaths that might be related to a larger plot.
The Hunt: This is the safest and most macabre hunting ground for a vampire in the city.
For Orion: A quick feed on a fresh corpse will bring him from Hungry to Stage 2: Satiated.
For Alfonso: This is the only location in the city where he can perform a True Feeding on a corpse, satisfying his unique hunger and allowing him to reach Stage 1: Gorged.




Vampire Hunt Assessment: Low Risk.

THE BLUE PALACE
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The Blue Palace stands as the magnificent heart of Solitude, a testament to Imperial grandeur and Nordic resilience. Inside, the great hall is a cavern of polished stone and soaring arches, its floors reflecting the light from tall, stained-glass windows. Courtiers in fine silks and velvets move with practiced grace, their conversations a low, conspiratorial murmur. Stern-faced Legionnaires stand at perfect attention, their presence a silent reminder that this is the center of power for the entire province."
Key NPCs Present:
Jarl Elisif the Fair: The High King's wife, often seen holding court or speaking with nobles.
Falk Firebeard: The Jarl's steward, a busy and serious man, often seen directing palace staff.
Sybille Stentor: The court wizard, a reclusive and ancient-looking woman who can usually be found in her chambers, surrounded by arcane artifacts.
Various Thanes, Courtiers, and Servants: The palace is a hub of political activity.


Player Opportunities:
Scout the Location: Players can use the daytime to familiarize themselves with the layout of the palace, noting guard positions and the general flow of traffic in preparation for their sundown audience.
Glean Courtly Gossip: Interacting with courtiers or servants (requires a successful Guile roll) can reveal rumors about the political tensions, Jarl Elisif's worries about Ulfric, or General Tullius's frustration with the Thalmor.
Consult the Court Wizard: A player might attempt to gain an audience with Sybille Stentor to ask about magical matters, though she is known to be curt and impatient with those who waste her time.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Suicidal. This is the most secure, well-lit, and heavily populated building in the city, second only to Castle Dour. Any hostile action would be met with an immediate and overwhelming response from the Royal Guard and Legionnaires.

THE BARDS COLLEGE  : ORION GOT IN FOR HALF OFF. 5% 3500 -200 3300
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The air around the Bards College is alive with sound. The gentle melody of a flute drifts from an upper window, competing with a student practicing a boisterous tavern song in the courtyard and the rhythmic beat of a drum from a practice hall. Inside, the halls smell of old books, lute wood, and beeswax. It is a place of creativity, history, and youthful ambition."
Key NPCs Present:
Viarmo: The Headmaster of the college, an Altmer with a flair for the dramatic, always seeking new stories for the annual festival.
Pantea Ateia, Giraud Gemane, Inge Six Fingers: Instructors and loremasters.
Numerous Bard Students: Practicing, studying, or composing throughout the building.


Player Opportunities:
Conduct Historical Research: This is the best place in Solitude for deep historical or mythological research. Players can request access to the college's library to look into ancient symbols (like the mark on Kyboh's gloves), forgotten legends, or the history of the Dragon Cult.
Commission a Song or Story: Players could speak with a student or instructor to have a specific piece of information turned into a song, potentially as a way to spread a message or rumor.
Impress the Masters: A player with a knack for performance could attempt to impress one of the instructors, potentially earning a small reward or a valuable piece of lore.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: High Risk. While a secluded library or storeroom might offer a moment of privacy, the college is filled with people at all hours. The risk of being discovered by a student or instructor is significant.

THE WINKING SKEEVER (INN)
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The Winking Skeever is the social heart of Solitude's market district. It's warm, surprisingly cozy, and filled with a lively mix of patrons. Off-duty Legionnaires share drinks with traveling merchants, grizzled sailors tell tall tales in a corner, and the innkeeper, a jovial Imperial named Corpulus, keeps the spiced wine flowing. The music of the bard Lisette provides a cheerful backdrop to the constant hum of conversation."
Key NPCs Present:
Corpulus Vinius: The cheerful and well-connected innkeeper.
Lisette: The resident bard, always on the lookout for a new story.
Off-Duty Legionnaires: A good source for barracks gossip or a friendly brawl.
Traveling Merchants: Can provide rumors from other holds.


Player Opportunities:
The Rumor Mill: This is the single best location in Solitude to gather general rumors. Players can learn about everything from the price of fish at the docks to the latest political tensions at the Blue Palace.
Hire Help (or a Distraction): A player could spend some coin to hire a mercenary for a short-term task or pay a group of drunks to start a brawl as a distraction.
Rest and Recover: The party's base of operations. They can rent rooms, get a hot meal, and store their gear safely.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: High Risk. While the inn is public, its patrons are often drunk and less attentive. A skilled vampire might be able to lure a drunken patron into the alley behind the inn for a quick feeding, but the risk of a guard patrol stumbling upon the scene is ever-present.

RADIANT RAIMENT (TAILOR & FINE GOODS)
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"Radiant Raiment is a bastion of high fashion and Imperial taste. The air smells of expensive perfumes and freshly dyed silks. Mannequins display the latest styles from the Imperial City, and bolts of vibrant, exotic fabrics are stacked neatly on shelves. The proprietors, two Altmer sisters, watch every customer with the sharp, appraising eyes of artisans judging a potential canvas—or a potential stain on their fine carpets."
Key NPCs Present:
Taarie: The more public-facing of the two sisters. She is haughty, dismissive, and obsessed with appearances.
Endarie: The true artist of the pair, usually found in the back, working meticulously on a garment. She is even less patient with common folk than her sister.


Player Opportunities:
Acquire Formal Wear: This is the only place in the city to purchase Fine Clothes. A player wanting to make a good impression at the Blue Palace might come here. The sisters will be brutally honest about their fashion sense.
Glean High-Society Gossip: Taarie is a conduit for the whispers of the court. A successful (and difficult) Guile roll to flatter her or impress her with a tale of high adventure might yield a rumor about the political maneuvering of Thane Erikur or the private anxieties of Jarl Elisif.
The Haggle (Preference: Vanity & Flattery): The sisters respond only to flattery about their work and their impeccable taste. Praising their artistry is the only way to get a better price. "At last, someone who understands true craftsmanship! For you, a special price."


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Very Poor. The shop is small, well-lit, and the proprietors are incredibly observant. There is no privacy and no viable targets.

THE LONELY TROLL (DOCKSIDE TAVERN)
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"If the Winking Skeever is the city's cheerful heart, the Lonely Troll is its drunken, salty gut. Located on the docks, this tavern is a dive in the truest sense. The air is thick with the smell of cheap ale, unwashed sailors, and spilled fish stew. The floor is sticky, the light is dim, and every conversation is a loud, slurred argument or a boastful sea shanty. Fights are common, and the City Guard only bothers to show up when someone draws a blade."
Key NPCs Present:
Gulum-Ei: A shifty Argonian often found in a dark corner, nursing a drink. He is a low-level informant for the Thieves Guild and other shady organizations.
A Motley Crew of Sailors: Men and women from across Tamriel, loud, drunk, and prone to gambling or violence.


Player Opportunities:
Gather Underworld Rumors: This is where you hear the things not spoken of in the upper city. A successful Guile roll (or a generous round of drinks) could yield information about smuggling routes, Thieves Guild activities, or which ships have "problems" with their cargo.
Find a Distraction: For a small price in gold, it would be trivially easy to start a massive brawl here, drawing the attention of any guards on the docks and creating a perfect window of opportunity for a clandestine activity elsewhere.
The Hunt: This is a prime hunting ground for a vampire. The patrons are drunk, inattentive, and transient. Luring a sailor into the back alley for a "private game of cards" or a "quiet drink" would be a viable, if still risky, strategy.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Good (but with risks). The chaotic environment provides excellent cover, but the targets are often armed and drunk, making them unpredictable.

THE EAST EMPIRE COMPANY WAREHOUSE
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"The East Empire Company Warehouse is a massive, imposing wooden structure that dominates the far end of the docks. It smells of foreign spices, tanned leather, and the immense wealth of the Empire. Heavily armed guards patrol the perimeter with professional vigilance, and you see scribes with clipboards meticulously checking manifests as cargo is loaded and unloaded. This is not just a building; it is a fortress of commerce."
Key NPCs Present:
Orthus Endario: An Imperial officer of the company, usually found overseeing operations. He is stressed, overworked, and has no time for anyone without an official appointment.
East Empire Wardens: The company's private security force. They are better equipped and more disciplined than the standard City Guard.


Player Opportunities:
Seek Information on Shipments: If investigating a specific piece of cargo or a person who arrived by sea (like Evette San's "lost" spices), this is the place to find the official records. Gaining access to the manifests would require a very high Guile roll (Persuasion with a plausible story, or Deception with a forged document) or a significant bribe.
Infiltration: Breaking into the warehouse would be a major stealth challenge. It is well-guarded day and night, but contains vast quantities of valuable goods and potentially sensitive shipping intelligence.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Suicidal. This location is as secure as Castle Dour, but with guards who are paid to be even more suspicious of outsiders. Any attempt to hunt here would end in a swift and lethal response.



THE FOUR SHIELDS TAVERN
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"A short walk from the bustling market, you find a tavern that feels like a piece of old Skyrim transplanted into the Imperial capital. The sign depicts four ancient, battered shields. Inside, the Four Shields Tavern is a world away from the Winking Skeever's bright polish. The air is thick with the smell of woodsmoke, roasting meat, and strong Nord mead. Low, heavy beams hang with drying herbs and hunting trophies. The patrons are almost exclusively Nords—grizzled dockworkers, old veterans, and proud citizens who speak in their native tongue, their conversations full of loud boasts and bitter complaints about the Empire and the Thalmor."
Key NPCs Present:
Odfel: The proprietor, an old, one-eyed Nord veteran who lost his eye in the Great War. He is deeply traditional and resentful of the Empire's weakness.
A rotating cast of traditionalist Nords: Good for hearing the "true" feelings of Solitude's native population.


Player Opportunities:
Hear the Opposition: This is the best place in the city to gather rumors about anti-Imperial sentiment, Thalmor activities, and pro-Stormcloak sympathies. Odfel is a font of traditionalist lore and grievances.
A Test of Allegiance: An openly pro-Imperial character will be met with cold stares and suspicious silence. A character who shows respect for Nord traditions (or buys a round of mead) will be welcomed into the conversation.
The Haggle (Preference: Faction Loyalty - Nord): Odfel has no time for Imperial flattery or clever words. He offers fair prices to those he considers "true Nords" at heart. "You respect the old ways. For you, the price is what it should be."
A More Volatile Hunt: The patrons are often drunk, but they are also proud, battle-hardened Nords. Luring one out for a feeding is possible, but they are far more likely to put up a serious fight than a common sailor.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Good (but with high combat risk). The patrons are less observant, but they are not easy prey.

THE GILDED SCROLL (MAGICAL GOODS & ENCHANTING)
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
"Tucked away on a quiet side street near the Blue Palace, this shop is a stark contrast to the city's open architecture. The interior is dim, smelling of old parchment, exotic reagents, and the sharp scent of ozone. Shelves overflow with dusty tomes, curiosities float in glowing jars, and an Arcane Enchanter hums softly in the corner, its purple light casting dancing shadows. It feels less like a shop and more like a scholar's private library."
Key NPCs Present:
Horatius: An anxious Imperial apprentice who manages the shop floor. He is terrified of his master, Sybille Stentor.
Sybille Stentor (Court Wizard): Rarely seen here, but her presence is felt in Horatius's constant, nervous mentions of "the Mistress."


Player Opportunities:
Purchase Magical Supplies: The primary location to buy Soul Gems, enchanting materials, and a limited selection of Spell Tomes (mostly Novice and Apprentice level).
Recharge & Enchant: For a fee, Horatius can use the Arcane Enchanter to recharge magical items. Custom enchantments are prohibitively expensive and require a "consultation with the Mistress."
The Haggle (Preference: Practical Knowledge): Horatius is an academic, not a merchant. He is impressed by magical knowledge. A successful Magic roll to discuss arcane theory or identify a rare item will earn his respect and a better price. "Ah, you recognize the Foci of Magnus in this staff's design? Remarkable! The Mistress appreciates a customer with a discerning eye."


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Poor. The shop is small and quiet, and Horatius is extremely observant. The back room is Sybille Stentor's private study, making it a very dangerous place to be caught snooping.

CASTLE DOUR DUNGEON (THE CONSEQUENCE)
Atmosphere (Read Aloud):
(If a player is arrested, read the following)
"You are stripped of your gear and thrown into a cold, damp cell in the dungeons beneath Castle Dour. The air is thick with the smell of mildew and despair. The only light comes from a single, sputtering torch in the corridor, casting long shadows that writhe like ghosts. The only sound is the drip of water and the distant, mournful groans of other prisoners. This is the end of the line in the Imperial capital."
Key NPCs Present:
A Grim Jailor: A nameless, silent Nord who delivers meager food and ignores all pleas or threats.


Player Opportunities (How to Get Out):
Pay the Bounty: The most straightforward option. An ally can pay the player's bounty to the jailor to secure their release.
Lockpicking: The cell door has a difficult lock (requires a Hard (-2) Guile roll to pick).
Serve the Sentence: Waiting out a sentence for a minor crime is possible, but it will consume all of the player's remaining Actions for the day, causing them to miss the audience with the King.
Jailbreak: A full-scale breakout is possible but extremely difficult. It would involve stealth and combat against the dungeon guards and would permanently mark the party as wanted criminals in Haafingar hold.


Vampire Hunt Assessment: Catastrophic. This is the ultimate failure state for a vampire. Being trapped in a cell, unable to feed, with the sun inevitably rising, is a death sentence. The threat of ending up here should make any Hunt in Solitude a tense and carefully considered decision.

