Part III: The Blue Palace Social Dungeon
GM Note on Framing: The Warden's Audition
This entire sequence is a test. High King Torygg has heard of the party's deeds, but he needs to see their character, judgment, and competence for himself before entrusting them with a Royal Charter. Krusp Fanck has been summoned for the same reason. The encounters in the palace are not random; they are a series of evaluations. How the party performs will directly influence the final outcome.
Scene 1: First Impressions
After the Order of Business, the party gathers and proceeds to the Blue Palace at sundown. Legate Quintus meets them at the gate and escorts them directly to the throne room, bypassing the usual petitioners.
Read Aloud:
"The Blue Palace is a monument to Imperial power, its soaring arches and polished marble floors echoing with the quiet bustle of the court. Jarls and Thanes in fine silks whisper in alcoves, while stern-faced Legionnaires stand at attention.
At the far end of the throne room, past the great fire pit, stands High King Torygg. He is younger than you expected, but carries himself with a quiet authority. Beside the throne stands General Tullius, his face a mask of military stoicism.
But what captures your attention first is the other figure already in audience. A lone warrior, clad in masterfully crafted but practical Steel Plate, his posture radiating a quiet, unshakable certainty. He turns as you approach, and his eyes—weary but sharp—assess you in a single glance.
Torygg rises slightly from his throne. 'Welcome, heroes,' he says, his voice carrying easily through the hall. 'Your deeds have preceded you.'"
Torygg's Opening (Corrected):
(Torygg rises slightly from his throne, his voice carrying a calm authority that belies his youth.)
"Welcome, heroes. Your names have reached my court with tales of impressive deeds."
(He gestures to the party, his gaze moving between them with genuine interest.)
"I have heard of a frozen tomb in Winterhold, its curse broken by a group of determined adventurers. Of a corrupted grove near Riften, cleansed by their hand. And of a darkness in Falkreath, driven back by their courage. You have proven you can work as one, a feat rarer than any magic."
(He then turns his gaze to the lone warrior, his tone shifting to one of deep respect.)
"And I have heard tales of a lone warrior, a blade in the darkness who hunts the monsters that plague our lands. They call you the Ashen Blade. A man who has accomplished alone what most companies of sellswords could not. Krusp Fanck."
Krusp's Introduction (Corrected):
(The warrior gives a respectful nod to the King, then turns his assessing gaze on the party. When he speaks, his voice is low, calm, and infused with a surprising warmth.)
"It is good to meet you. The King spoke of your deeds. It is rare to find those who stand against the dark with such conviction."
(He offers a simple, genuine nod of acknowledgment.)
"I am Krusp Fanck. I am here because the High King asked it of me."
GM Note: This immediately establishes the two candidates for the Wardens: the collaborative party and the legendary solo operator.

ENCOUNTER 1: General Tullius's Scrutiny (The Test of Mettle)
Before Torygg can continue, General Tullius steps forward.
General Tullius (Master NPC)
Stats: Might 18, Agility 10, Magic 8, Guile 16
Read Aloud:
"General Tullius, commander of the Imperial Legion, steps forward. He addresses Torygg, but his skeptical eyes are fixed on you.
'Your Majesty, with respect, I must voice my concerns. These... freelancers operate outside any command structure. Why should the Crown trust them with matters of state security when their only loyalty is to coin?'"
The Challenge: This is a Hard (-2) Guile check. The party must convince Tullius of their worth.
Special Modifiers:
If Davinia makes the argument, she gains Advantage (due to her father's legacy).
If the party mentions specific innocent lives they saved, they gain a +2 bonus to their Guile Target Number for the roll.


Outcomes:
Success: Tullius nods grudgingly. "Very well. But I will be watching." The party gains the "Legion's Measured Trust" tag (future interactions with Imperial officers are at Standard difficulty).
Failure: Tullius remains unconvinced. "I have stated my objections, Your Majesty." The party gains the "Legion Scrutiny" tag (all future interactions with Imperial officers are made with a -2 penalty to their Target Number).
Critical Success (Roll of 1): Tullius is genuinely impressed, offering a forearm clasp. "Perhaps I misjudged you." The party gains the "Legion's Respect" tag (Advantage on one future request for Imperial aid).
Critical Failure (Roll of 20): Tullius scoffs. "Typical mercenary talk." The party gains "Tullius's Disdain" tag (the General will actively work to undermine them in Imperial territories).
Krusp's Response: Krusp remains silent. He produces a scroll—a list of his completed contracts, each verified by a Jarl. He hands it to Tullius without a word. Tullius reads it, nods once, and says, "Your record is impeccable, Fanck." Krusp simply nods back. He has passed the test through professionalism alone.

ENCOUNTER 2: The Whispering Court (The Test of Discretion)
After Tullius's challenge, Torygg speaks:
"I must attend to another matter briefly. In the meantime, please—enjoy the hospitality of my court."
The Goal: The party has 30 minutes to mingle. This is a test of their ability to gather intelligence subtly. Torygg is watching.
Key NPCs:
Jarl Elisif the Fair (Guile 10): If approached with empathy (Standard Guile check), she will confide her fears about Torygg's safety and Ulfric's open challenges to his legitimacy.
Thane Bryling (Guile 14): If approached with political acumen (Hard (-2) Guile check), she reveals that the party's mission is not just about dragons, but about proving Torygg's strength to the wavering Jarls.
Thane Erikur (Guile 12, Untrustworthy): He will approach the party and try to gauge their loyalty, asking what they "really think" of the King. A Standard Guile check is required to see through his trap and deflect.
The Puzzle Solution: If the party speaks to at least two NPCs and succeeds, they gain the "Political Awareness" tag, understanding the mission's true stakes.
Krusp's Actions: Krusp does not mingle. He stands near a pillar, observing the party's interactions, assessing their character.

ENCOUNTER 3: The Thalmor Confrontation (The Test of Judgment)
As the party is about to be called back, a commotion erupts in the courtyard, visible from the throne room's large windows. Torygg, Tullius, and the court all turn to watch.
The Setup: Three Thalmor Justiciars are arresting a young Nord for Talos worship. This is a live-fire moral and political test.
The Thalmor Justiciars (Adept Tier, TL 1 each)
Stats: Might 14, Agility 14, Magic 16, Guile 16
The Challenge: To intervene, the party must make a Very Hard (-4) Guile check.
Special Modifiers:
If they invoke the King's authority ("We are the King's agents..."): +2 bonus to their Guile Target Number.
If they threaten violence: -4 penalty to their Guile Target Number.


Outcomes:
Success: The Justiciars reluctantly release the boy. The party gains "Thalmor Scrutiny" (-2 penalty to future interactions with Thalmor) but also "Hero of the People" (Advantage on social rolls with common Nords). Torygg is visibly impressed.
Failure: The Justiciars refuse and take the boy. Torygg notes their attempt but is disappointed by the failure.
Do Nothing: The boy is taken. The crowd sees them as cowards. Torygg is deeply disappointed.
Krusp's Action: The moment the party chooses to intervene, Krusp moves to stand with them. He places his hand on Dawnbringer's hilt but says nothing. His action is a silent declaration of support, a physical show of force to back up the party's words. He is demonstrating his core principle: he will always stand between a predator and its prey.

ENCOUNTER 4: The Audience with the King (The Final Interview)
The party and Krusp are called before the throne. The room is now private.
Read Aloud:
"Torygg looks at you, his expression thoughtful. 'I have seen enough. I saw how you handled the General's doubts, and I witnessed your judgment in the courtyard.' He leans forward. 'Before I make my decision, I have one question: Why do you do this? What drives you to risk your lives for a world that is falling apart?'"
The Final Test: This is not a skill check. It is pure roleplay. Torygg wants to hear their motivations in their own words.
Krusp's Response: If asked, Krusp will answer simply.
"I made an oath. To stand between the innocent and the darkness. That is all."
Torygg's Decision: Based on their answers and their performance, Torygg makes his final judgment. Assuming they have not catastrophically failed, he will proceed.
"Skyrim needs heroes, not just soldiers or politicians. It needs people who will act. I have made my decision."

