His Response:
If they say no: "Good. Then you'll listen when I tell you: they're not like other monsters. They think. They plan. And their Thu'um..." (He shakes his head) "Just... stay behind cover when it breathes. Always."


If they claim yes (lying or exaggerating): He studies them carefully. "Really. Where?" (If they can't give a convincing answer, he just says) "Hmm." (And drops it, but he's noted they're either liars or fools)



Midday (On the Road, Before the Roar)
Setup: The journey is peaceful. Too peaceful. Birds are singing, sun is shining.
Krusp initiates: He's been quiet for an hour, just watching the forest. Then:
"When we get to Kynesgrove... if it's bad... if there are survivors..."
(He chooses his words carefully)
"They'll be traumatized. Terrified. Some of them might not be rational. Don't take it personally if they don't trust us immediately. Just... do the job. Help them. The gratitude comes later, if at all."
(Pause)
"That's the work. Not the glory the bards sing about. Just... showing up when no one else will."
